{"id":"1811.08303","submitter":"Y. M. Cho","authors":"Y. M. Cho, Franklin H. Cho","title":"Abelian Decomposition and Weyl Symmetric Effective Action of SU(3) QCD","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:1606.02374","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1140/epjc/s10052-019-7023-x","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show how to calculate the effective potential of SU(3) QCD which tells\nthat the true minimum is given by the monopole condensation. To do this we make\nthe gauge independent Weyl symmetric Abelian decomposition of the SU(3) QCD\nwhich decomposes the gluons to the color neutral neurons and the colored\nchromons. In the perturbative regime this decomposes the Feynman diagram in\nsuch a way that the conservation of color is explicit. Moreover, this shows the\nexistence of two gluon jets, the neuron jet and chromon jet, which can be\nverified by experiment. In the non-perturbative regime, the decomposition puts\nQCD to the background field formalism and reduces the non-Abelian gauge\nsymmetry to a discrete color reflection symmetry, and provides us an ideal\nplatform to calculate the one-loop effective action of QCD. Integrating out the\nchromons from the Weyl symmetric Abelian decomposition of QCD gauge invariantly\nimposing the color reflection invariance, we obtain the SU(3) QCD effective\npotential which generates the stable monopole condensation and the mass gap. We\ndiscuss the physical implications of our result, in particular the possible\nexistence of the vacuum fluctuation mode of the monopole condensation in QCD.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 17 Nov 2018 02:00:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-24"}
